  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Mandates reporting of suspicious activities\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Makes money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Prohibits transactions designed to conceal the source of illegal funds\n\n3. Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988\n- Expanded money laundering statutes to include drug-related crimes\n\n4. Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n- Enhanced requirements for reporting suspicious activities\n- Increased penalties for money laundering offenses\n\n5. USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Strengthened anti-money laundering regulations\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Increased cooperation between financial institutions and law enforcement\n\n6. Corporate Transparency Act of 2021\n- Requires companies to report beneficial ownership information\n- Aims to prevent money laundering through shell companies\n\nAt the federal level, these statutes provide comprehensive legal frameworks for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities. Penalties can include significant fines and imprisonment.",
